Acts as the root of all Java classes, i.e. Every class implicitly extends Object.

Example: Car car = new Car();

        car → reference variable
        new Car() → actual object in heap
        car stores memory address

What happens internally:
    -Memory allocated in heap
    -Constructor is called
    -Reference stored in variable

Important Object Class Methods:

| Method               | Purpose                       |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| `toString()`         | String representation         |
| `equals(Object obj)` | Compare objects               |
| `hashCode()`         | Hash value                    |
| `clone()`            | Copy object                   |
| `getClass()`         | Returns class metadata        |
| `finalize()`         | Called before GC (deprecated) |
| `wait()`             | Thread communication          |
| `notify()`           | Thread communication          |
| `notifyAll()`        | Thread communication          |


Default Behavior of Object Methods
If you don’t override:

| Method     | Default Behavior     |
| ---------- | -------------------- |
| equals()   | Reference comparison |
| hashCode() | Based on memory      |
| toString() | ClassName@hash       |
